1682","1671":"1671","ABT 1600":"about 1600","1590":"1590","1600":"1600","1610":"1610","1687":"1687","ABT 1671":"about 1671","1620":"1620","BEF 1662":"before 1662","1662":"1662","1618":"1618","24 MAR 1687":"24 March 1687","1648":"1648","Plaine,67420,Bas-Rhin,Grand Est,FRANCE,Principauté de Salm":"Plaine, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France","Plaine,67420,Bas-Rhin,Grand Est,FRANCE,":"Plaine, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"THEODORE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Serge, Henri, Pierre, Alide, Andre, Antoine, Benoit, Berthony, Chantal, Daphnee, Edouard, Guilene.","French and Mauritian (<b>Théodore</b>); West Indian (in Haiti, Martinique, and Guadeloupe <b>Théodore</b>); English and Welsh: from a personal name derived from Greek <i>Theodōros</i>, a compound of <i>theos</i> ‘God’ + <i>dōron</i> ‘gift’, which was relatively popular in the Middle Ages because of its auspicious meaning. The name was borne by several early Christian saints. There was considerable confusion with the ancient Germanic name <i>Theodoric</i> (see   Terry  ). In Wales, the personal name <i>Theodore</i> was also adopted as an approximation to the Welsh name <i>Tewdwr</i> (see   Tudor  ). In North America, this surname has absorbed various other European cognates and their derivatives, e.g. Greek   Theodorakis  , Macedonian <b>Todorovski</b>, and Serbian <b>Todorović</b> (see   Todorovic  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Tadros","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Samir, Hany, Ashraf, Maher, Fakhry, Maged, Nader, Youssef, Adly, Adnan, Amani, Anwar.","Arabic (mainly Egypt): from the Arabic personal name <i>Tadros</i>, Greek <i>Theodōros</i> (see   Theodore  ), found among Christians. Compare   Tawadros  ."]},{"name":"Teodorescu","meanings":["Romanian: patronymic, with the suffix <i>-escu</i>, from the personal name <i>Teodor</i> (see   Theodore  )."]},{"name":"Teodoro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Jorge, Rodrigo, Arturo, Carlos, Domingo, Elvira, Erlinda, Gavino, Gustavo, Jacinto.  Italian Antonio, Donato, Nunzio, Umberto.  Portuguese Duarte, Joao.","Spanish and Italian: from the personal name <i>Teodoro</i> (see   Theodore  )."]},{"name":"Terry","meanings":["English and Irish: from the Norman personal name <i>T(h)erry</i> (Old French <i>Thierri</i>), a short form of <i>Theodoric</i>, which is composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>theud</i> ‘people, race’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful), rich’. <i>Theodoric</i> was the name of the Ostrogothic leader (<i>c.</i> 454–526) who invaded Italy in 488 and established his capital at Ravenna in 493. His name was sometimes taken as a derivative of Greek <i>Theodōros</i> (see   Theodore  ). An Anglo-Norman family of this name has been in County Cork, Ireland, since the 13th century.","Irish: sometimes an Anglicized (‘translated’) form of Gaelic <b>Mac Toirdhealbhaigh</b> (see   Turley  )."]},{"name":"Todaro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Angelo, Mario, Sal, Biagio, Carlo, Carmine, Giuseppe, Alicia, Antonio, Giovanni, Liborio, Marcello, Onofrio, Rocco.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Todaro</i>, a variant of <i>Teodoro</i>, from Greek <i>Theodōros</i> (see   Theodore  )."]},{"name":"Theodoropoulos","meanings":["Greek: patronymic from the personal name <i>Theodōros</i> (see   Theodore  ) + the ending <i>-poulos</i> (from Latin <i>pullus</i> ‘nestling, chick’), which occurs chiefly in the Peloponnese."]},{"name":"Theo","meanings":["American shortened form of any of various Greek patronymics from the personal name <i>Theodōros</i> (see   Theodore  ), such as   Theodorakis  ,   Theodoridis  ,   Theodoropoulos  , and   Theodorou  ."]},{"name":"Theodorou","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Greek Andreas, Stavros, Stelios, Anastasios, Christos, Demetrios, Dimitrios, Dimitris, Dimitrois, Evangelos, Kostas, Nicolaos.","Greek: patronymic from the genitive case of the personal name <i>Theodōros</i> (see   Theodore  )."]},{"name":"Theodorakis","meanings":["Greek: patronymic from the personal name <i>Theodōros</i> (see   Theodore  ) + the diminutive suffix <i>-akis</i>, which is particularly typical for the surnames from Crete, where it was adopted massively in the 19th century."]},{"name":"Theodoridis","meanings":["Greek: patronymic from the personal name <i>Theodōros</i> (see   Theodore  ). The suffix <i>-idis</i>, meaning ‘son/descendant of’, is a variant of the classical <i>-ides</i> which was revived in the 19th century, in particular by Greeks from Asia Minor and Eastern Thrace."]}]},{"name":"Odile","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the medieval Germanic name <i>Odila</i>, a derivative of <i>od</i> meaning ‘prosperity, wealth’; borne by a 8th-century saint who founded a Benedictine convent at what is now Odilienburg in Alsace; she is the patron saint of Alsace."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1355839,"age":10,"year":"1610","julianDay":2309101,"description":"Reigns of Louis XIII and Louis XIV. Royal power at its peak. France dominates Europe, French culture spreads. Start of large-scale sea trade.","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1670188,"age":18,"year":"1618","toYear":"1648","julianDay":2312023,"title":"30 Years War","description":"Ferdinand II was trying to force the people to follow Catholicism. The 30 years war was a battle of religion with the Protestants and Catholics, in the Holy Roman Empire.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/reformation/thirty-years-war","urlTitle":"History-Thirty Years' War","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1670166,"age":82,"year":"1682","julianDay":2335399,"title":"The Palace of Versailles","description":"The Palace of Versailles was originally known as a hunting log and retreat for Louis XII. When Louis XIV took over he moved his family into it. After he died the palace was abandoned. It has since been turned into a museum.","url":"https://www.britannica.com/topic/Palace-of-Versailles","urlTitle":"Encyclopedia Britannica- Palace of Versailles","jurisdictionLevel":3}],"lifeSummary":"Odile THEODORE was born about 1600 as the daughter of Jean Théodore. She married Nicolas BURQUART about 1620, in Plaine, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died on 24 March 1687, in Plaine, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France, at the age of 88."},"et":{"ABT 1600–24 MAR 1687":"umbes 1600–24. märts 1687","1600–1687":"1600–1687","1590–1662":"1590–1662","1620–1671":"1620–1671","–Male":"Surnud","ABT 1620":"umbes 1620","1682":"1682","1671":"1671","ABT 1600":"umbes 1600","1590":"1590","1600":"1600","1610":"1610","1687":"1687","ABT 1671":"umbes 1671","1620":"1620","BEF 1662":"enne 1662","1662":"1662","1618":"1618","24 MAR 1687":"24. märts 1687","1648":"1648","Plaine,67420,Bas-Rhin,Grand Est,FRANCE,Principauté de Salm":"Plaine, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, Prantsusmaa","Plaine,67420,Bas-Rhin,Grand Est,FRANCE,":"Plaine, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"ABT 1600–24 MAR 1687":"noin 1600–24. maaliskuuta 1687","1600–1687":"1600–1687","1590–1662":"1590–1662","1620–1671":"1620–1671","–Male":"Kuollut","ABT 1620":"noin 1620","1682":"1682","1671":"1671","ABT 1600":"noin 1600","1590":"1590","1600":"1600","1610":"1610","1687":"1687","ABT 1671":"noin 1671","1620":"1620","BEF 1662":"ennen vuotta 1662","1662":"1662","1618":"1618","24 MAR 1687":"24. maaliskuuta 1687","1648":"1648","Plaine,67420,Bas-Rhin,Grand Est,FRANCE,Principauté de Salm":"Plaine, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, Ranska","Plaine,67420,Bas-Rhin,Grand Est,FRANCE,":"Plaine, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, Ranska"},"fr":{"ABT 1600–24 MAR 1687":"environ 1600–24 mars 1687","1600–1687":"1600–1687","1590–1662":"1590–1662","1620–1671":"1620–1671","–Male":"Décédé","ABT 1620":"environ 1620","1682":"1682","1671":"1671","ABT 1600":"environ 1600","1590":"1590","1600":"1600","1610":"1610","1687"